What happened was that new generation of anti-racist thinkers realized, actually, it's the way we talk about human differences that creates those differences.
Those differences don't exist naturally in a state of nature, as it were.
And so allowing racist speech to circulate is one of the preconditions for a racist social order.
So it follows from there that if you want to overthrow a racist social order, you have to put certain blockages or closures on racist speech, because the two are entwined.
That's what led to a lot of U.S. colleges and universities developing different speech codes that created some community guidelines, essentially, around sexist, racist, and homophobic speech.
They saw that actually if you enable racist speech to circulate freely, or sexist speech, or homophobic speech, it actually shores up a sexist or a homophobic social order.
But Anshu said that people on the other side of things then realized, hold on, if we want to maintain the social order, we need people to keep saying racist, sexist things.
